WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.720
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:06.220 --> 00:00:07.520
&gt;&gt; Nora Krug: Welcome.

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:08.820
&gt;&gt; Marie Lu: Thank you.

00:00:08.820 --> 00:00:10.120
&gt;&gt; Nora Krug: Thank you for coming.

00:00:10.120 --> 00:00:12.780
It's my great pleasure to be
here today to talk with Marie Lu.

00:00:12.780 --> 00:00:17.160 position:56%
As most of you, probably all of you
know, she is the best-selling author

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:21.060
of the Legend and Young Elite
Series, books that have swept us

00:00:21.060 --> 00:00:24.460
through time and taken us through
thrilling places and introduce us

00:00:24.460 --> 00:00:28.620
to all sorts of dark and
complicated characters.

00:00:28.620 --> 00:00:34.140
Her new book, which I was lucky
enough to get early, is Warcross.

00:00:34.140 --> 00:00:36.510
It comes out in 10 days.

00:00:36.510 --> 00:00:42.190
[ Applause ]

00:00:42.190 --> 00:00:45.660 position:56%
So I've had the privilege of
reading the book before it came out,

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:48.730
and I can tell you that it
will keep you up all night,

00:00:48.730 --> 00:00:50.070
but it won't give you nightmares.

00:00:50.070 --> 00:00:53.110
It's a lot of fun.

00:00:53.110 --> 00:00:58.690
So this time, she takes us into
a world that she knows very well.

00:00:58.690 --> 00:01:03.480
It's about video games, and as you
may know, she previously worked

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:07.130
in the videogame industry, and
here she uses that experience

00:01:07.130 --> 00:01:11.610
to create a very exciting story
set in the not-so-distant future

00:01:11.610 --> 00:01:15.910
about another bad-ass
girl, if I can say that.

00:01:15.910 --> 00:01:17.210
&gt;&gt; Marie Lu: Yes.

00:01:17.210 --> 00:01:18.510 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Nora Krug: Yeah, she's a bad ass,

00:01:18.510 --> 00:01:19.840
but I'm not sure I'm
supposed to use that word.

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:22.280
&gt;&gt; Marie Lu: It's okay.

00:01:22.280 --> 00:01:23.810
&gt;&gt; Nora Krug: I said nice, but,

00:01:23.810 --> 00:01:27.270
she's a bounty hunter
named Emika Chen,

00:01:27.270 --> 00:01:30.750
and her life gets pretty
complicated when she hacks

00:01:30.750 --> 00:01:35.200
into an immersive video game that's
sweeping, taking over the world.

00:01:35.200 --> 00:01:39.170
The book raises some very
thought-provoking questions

00:01:39.170 --> 00:01:42.880
about technology, but it's also
just a really exciting story

00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:47.500 position:56%
about a rainbow-haired heroine that
I think you're really going to love.

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:48.800
&gt;&gt; Marie Lu: Thank you.

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:50.620
&gt;&gt; Nora Krug: And congratulations
on your book.

00:01:50.620 --> 00:01:54.160
I'm just going to give you a
little preview of the book.

00:01:54.160 --> 00:01:57.400
It's a teaser, not a spoiler.

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:01.920
So it's a bit of a change for
you after The Young Elites.

00:02:01.920 --> 00:02:04.530
It's a little more personal, maybe,

00:02:04.530 --> 00:02:08.500
and it's back to Science Fiction
a bit after writing fantasy

00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:09.880
in Young Elites, and I just wanted

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:15.680
to ask what made you decide
to go in that direction?

00:02:15.680 --> 00:02:18.200
&gt;&gt; Marie Lu: Sure, yeah, first
of all, thank you so much

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:19.500
for having me here at the festival.

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:21.220
This is my first time at
The National Book Festival.

00:02:21.220 --> 00:02:27.120
So I'm really excited to
be here to see you guys.

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:28.420
Thank you.

00:02:28.420 --> 00:02:29.980
Thank you for being here.

00:02:29.980 --> 00:02:34.280
And I -- so before I became a
full-time writer, I used it to work

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:38.710
in video games, like you said,
and so I always knew that I wanted

00:02:38.710 --> 00:02:42.150 position:56%
to write something to do with games.

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:44.450
I just didn't know what
that story would be yet.

00:02:44.450 --> 00:02:49.520
I started with the Legend
Series, and Legend is a dark,

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:54.480
futuristic story set in Los
Angeles about 100 years from now,

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:59.640
and when I was developing the
Legend world, I made this bit

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:03.850
of world building that I wanted to
expand on, and in the Legend world,

00:03:03.850 --> 00:03:07.590
there is a society
set in Antarctica,

00:03:07.590 --> 00:03:09.580
which is now a habitable
place, because, you know,

00:03:09.580 --> 00:03:16.220
climate change is real, and
in this futuristic Antarctica,

00:03:16.220 --> 00:03:19.790
every part of the society
is completely gamified,

00:03:19.790 --> 00:03:23.320
and what that means is you
water a plant, you get a point.

00:03:23.320 --> 00:03:24.620
You know, you go to school

00:03:24.620 --> 00:03:27.590
and answer a test question
correctly, you get five points.

00:03:27.590 --> 00:03:31.850
You level up in society that
way, and as you level up,

00:03:31.850 --> 00:03:35.940
you get perks in life or, you
know, better access to stuff,

00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:38.640
and that was how the society
worked, and I was only able

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:43.330
to use a very tiny part of that
when I wrote Legend's but I wanted

00:03:43.330 --> 00:03:46.190 position:56%
to do something more with that idea.

00:03:46.190 --> 00:03:48.800
So I kind of kept that idea
in the back of my head.

00:03:48.800 --> 00:03:52.850 position:56%
It was like this little thing on the
shelf that I wanted to get back to.

00:03:52.850 --> 00:03:55.010
So then I wrote the Young
Elite Series which is,

00:03:55.010 --> 00:03:57.470
you know, very dark fantasy.

00:03:57.470 --> 00:03:59.680
It's about a girl who
essentially the teen girl version

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:03.880
of Darth Vader, and her
downfall to the dark side.

00:04:03.880 --> 00:04:08.050
So I was writing The Young
Elites feeling very emo

00:04:08.050 --> 00:04:11.650
and depressed all this time,
because I kind of did not think

00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:13.620
through the idea of,
oh, it'll be fun to be

00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:15.770
in a villain's head,
but for four years.

00:04:15.770 --> 00:04:19.130
So I was about half way through
writing The Young Elites,

00:04:19.130 --> 00:04:21.290
and I love that series so much.

00:04:21.290 --> 00:04:26.340
It means a lot to me, but it was so
heavy, so heavy and hard to write

00:04:26.340 --> 00:04:30.230 position:56%
that I had to have a palate cleanser
at the end of every workday.

00:04:30.230 --> 00:04:33.270
So I started writing this
book called Warcross.

00:04:33.270 --> 00:04:35.270
At the end of every workday
when I was like, ugh,

00:04:35.270 --> 00:04:37.220
I can't be in The Young
Elites world anymore.

00:04:37.220 --> 00:04:38.520
I need something fun.

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:40.100
I need something happy.

00:04:40.100 --> 00:04:44.000
I would start world building
out of that little bit

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.000
of world and the idea in Legend.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:48.960
So I started expanding
on this idea of this game

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:52.900
that would just sweep the world,
that everybody would love to play,

00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:56.790
that was based on virtual
reality and augmented reality

00:04:56.790 --> 00:04:59.360
and all this new technology
that's coming out,

00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:01.970
and I would do a little bit of
that every night, and it would kind

00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:03.590
of cheer me up again
and get be ready

00:05:03.590 --> 00:05:06.490
to go again the next
day at The Young Elites.

00:05:06.490 --> 00:05:11.570
So that's what I did, and as I
did that, Emika Chen came to me,

00:05:11.570 --> 00:05:14.170
and she came very fully formed.

00:05:14.170 --> 00:05:16.040
She always had her rainbow hair.

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:17.470 position:56%
For anyone who's ever read my books,

00:05:17.470 --> 00:05:20.450
you know I have an
obsession with hair.

00:05:20.450 --> 00:05:23.090
Everyone I like in my
books has nice hair.

00:05:23.090 --> 00:05:25.530
So Emika has the best hair.

00:05:25.530 --> 00:05:26.830
She has like every
color you can think

00:05:26.830 --> 00:05:31.250
of in her hair, and she's a hacker.

00:05:31.250 --> 00:05:32.550
She's a tech girl.

00:05:32.550 --> 00:05:37.640
She's a gamer girl, and she's
struggling to get by and trying to,

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:41.070
you know, do the right thing, and
her personality and heart kind

00:05:41.070 --> 00:05:46.950
of melded with the idea of this
game that takes the world by storm,

00:05:46.950 --> 00:05:50.110
and from there, you know,
Warcross kind of took off,

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:52.370
and I think it was
probably the most fun thing

00:05:52.370 --> 00:05:54.340
that I've ever gotten to write.

00:05:54.340 --> 00:05:58.300
I had a really good time
writing it, which is odd for me.

00:05:58.300 --> 00:06:00.910
Usually, I struggle a
lot with my first drafts,

00:06:00.910 --> 00:06:02.920
and not to say I didn't
struggle with Warcross,

00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:05.640
but it was a more fun struggle.

00:06:05.640 --> 00:06:09.640
&gt;&gt; Nora Krug: So how much
of your experience working

00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:12.810
in the videogame industry
is in the book?

00:06:12.810 --> 00:06:15.100
&gt;&gt; Marie Lu: There's -- yeah,
that's a great question,

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:17.090
because there actually are
a lot of little anecdotes

00:06:17.090 --> 00:06:19.210
that crept into the story.

00:06:19.210 --> 00:06:21.040
Sometimes unconsciously.

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:24.510
When I first started working
in games, I hopped into a kind

00:06:24.510 --> 00:06:26.190
of spontaneously I
was supposed to go

00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:28.740
to law school, which didn't happen.

00:06:28.740 --> 00:06:32.350
Apparently, my personality
just does not match with that,

00:06:32.350 --> 00:06:34.900
and the thing is, I loved my
political science classes.

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:37.240
Love, love, loved them, and a
lot of that still creeps back

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:39.430
into my writing all the time,

00:06:39.430 --> 00:06:42.640
but I didn't have quite the right
personality to be, you know,

00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:47.130
at court in trial or going
through trial cases are anything.

00:06:47.130 --> 00:06:50.240
So, you know, at the end of the
school year, I was kind of like,

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:52.030
all right, am I really
going to do this?

00:06:52.030 --> 00:06:57.190
And I stumbled across this kiosk
on campus that had a bulletin

00:06:57.190 --> 00:07:00.690
from Disney, Interactive Studios
and I applied and got into that.

00:07:00.690 --> 00:07:05.410
So I ended up in games, but I had
the best time that I've ever had

00:07:05.410 --> 00:07:08.130
in a corporate job at Disney.

00:07:08.130 --> 00:07:13.710
What it was was it was a
think tank with eight interns,

00:07:13.710 --> 00:07:16.340
and they put us all in this
warehouse-like room in the middle

00:07:16.340 --> 00:07:22.520 position:56%
of the Disney campus, and they just
told us come up with new game ideas,

00:07:22.520 --> 00:07:24.980
and every Tuesday, you'd
pitch your game ideas.

00:07:24.980 --> 00:07:27.070
If we like it, we'll greenlight it.

00:07:27.070 --> 00:07:29.530
You know, you get to pitch it
to Bob Iger, who is the CEO

00:07:29.530 --> 00:07:30.830
of Disney, and all of that.

00:07:30.830 --> 00:07:35.360
So it was an incredibly fun job,
and the first time I was immersed

00:07:35.360 --> 00:07:38.680
with seven other interns who
were also in the creative arts.

00:07:38.680 --> 00:07:42.990
So we had a lot of fun, and
a lot of Emika's teammates,

00:07:42.990 --> 00:07:47.140
and people that she comes across
in Warcross are very much based

00:07:47.140 --> 00:07:48.900
on people that I was friends

00:07:48.900 --> 00:07:52.940
with that I very much
enjoyed spending time with.

00:07:52.940 --> 00:07:55.200
You know, we would -- we worked
together eight hours a day,

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:57.710
but after work ended, we
would still play, you know,

00:07:57.710 --> 00:07:59.970
Mario Kart for an hour together.

00:07:59.970 --> 00:08:02.140
We had like a fake wrestler
belt and everything.

00:08:02.140 --> 00:08:05.110
We had, you know, blue shells
and green shells on it,

00:08:05.110 --> 00:08:08.060
and if you won the last round
of the day, you got to hang it

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:09.360
over your desk the next day.

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:11.500
It was like this big status symbol.

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:13.010
In the company, like
our bosses would come

00:08:13.010 --> 00:08:15.150
and challenge us for it and stuff.

00:08:15.150 --> 00:08:18.710
So it was really fun, and
Mario Kart makes its way

00:08:18.710 --> 00:08:20.010
into the book, as well.

00:08:20.010 --> 00:08:21.310
That was an anecdote.

00:08:21.310 --> 00:08:22.610
&gt;&gt; Nora Krug: And one of your dogs.

00:08:22.610 --> 00:08:23.910
&gt;&gt; Marie Lu: And one of my dogs.

00:08:23.910 --> 00:08:25.480
Yes, Amber Corgi.

00:08:25.480 --> 00:08:29.090
And there is a Corgi who walks
across the stream, the page,

00:08:29.090 --> 00:08:32.440
at one point in the story,
because I was like, you know,

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:33.960
this book has all of my
favorite things in it.

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:37.580
So I'm going to throw
my dog in there too.

00:08:37.580 --> 00:08:40.840
&gt;&gt; Nora Krug: So I bet a lot
of people here, who, obviously,

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:43.840
haven't read the book are
still thinking about Adelina,

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:47.500
who is a complicated
and darker character,

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:48.940
and you've called her
kind of Darth Vader.

00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:52.500
So I assume you're
a big Star Wars fan.

00:08:52.500 --> 00:08:54.390
&gt;&gt; Marie Lu: Oh, yeah.

00:08:54.390 --> 00:08:58.490 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Nora Krug: I guess, what made you
want to create such a complicated

00:08:58.490 --> 00:09:01.220
and sometimes unlikable character,

00:09:01.220 --> 00:09:04.350
especially when you're
writing for a young audience?

00:09:04.350 --> 00:09:07.090
It seems like it's kind
of a risk to do that.

00:09:07.090 --> 00:09:11.640
So what was your motivation,
and how has that worked out?

00:09:11.640 --> 00:09:13.700
&gt;&gt; Marie Lu: Yeah, I
don't know why it is that.

00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:16.260
But I've always kind of
gravitated towards dark stories,

00:09:16.260 --> 00:09:17.560
ever since I was little.

00:09:17.560 --> 00:09:21.950
Like I think I was like 7, and
I would write wanted reports,

00:09:21.950 --> 00:09:26.090
like fake wanted reports of fake
criminals, because I saw them

00:09:26.090 --> 00:09:29.090
on corkboards all the
time, and so I made

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:33.150
up wanted criminals all the time.

00:09:33.150 --> 00:09:34.970
You know, Legend is
about a teen criminal,

00:09:34.970 --> 00:09:36.340
and it's about a dystopian society.

00:09:36.340 --> 00:09:38.830
So The Young Elites is kind
of an extension of that,

00:09:38.830 --> 00:09:41.070
but it is definitely the darkest
story that I've ever written,

00:09:41.070 --> 00:09:44.110
and I think it came about
because I really wanted

00:09:44.110 --> 00:09:46.350
to explore the villain's journey.

00:09:46.350 --> 00:09:51.490
Because, you know, villains are
still people, and I think a lot

00:09:51.490 --> 00:09:54.540
of times, people have a have
a tendency to label villains

00:09:54.540 --> 00:09:58.160
as monsters, to kind of
distance themselves from humans.

00:09:58.160 --> 00:09:59.810
You know, like humans are human.

00:09:59.810 --> 00:10:03.040
How can a human possibly
do horrible things?

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:05.650
We call them a monster
instead, but the worst monsters

00:10:05.650 --> 00:10:07.860
in our history have been human.

00:10:07.860 --> 00:10:09.170
You know, they are people.

00:10:09.170 --> 00:10:11.250
People are capable
of terrible things,

00:10:11.250 --> 00:10:12.920
and how do they get to that point?

00:10:12.920 --> 00:10:15.950
And the other path of
it is everyone thinks

00:10:15.950 --> 00:10:17.640
that they're the hero, you know?

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:19.640
Even the villain, from
their point of view,

00:10:19.640 --> 00:10:20.940
thinks that they're the hero.

00:10:20.940 --> 00:10:23.950
Darth Vader probably thought
he was doing the right thing,

00:10:23.950 --> 00:10:25.740
you know, for quite a while.

00:10:25.740 --> 00:10:27.780
Magneto thought he was
doing the right thing.

00:10:27.780 --> 00:10:29.980
Loki thought he was
doing the right thing.

00:10:29.980 --> 00:10:31.900
And in the process,
they become beasts.

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:35.190
You know, they do these terrible,
terrible things in the name

00:10:35.190 --> 00:10:37.280
of what they think is justice.

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:44.350
So I wanted to explore the story of
this girl who starts off the story,

00:10:44.350 --> 00:10:47.450
you know, kind of in a
neutral ground, and slowly,

00:10:47.450 --> 00:10:51.340
through the course of terrible
injustices that happen to her,

00:10:51.340 --> 00:10:55.810
falls apart, because what
happens when you don't rise up,

00:10:55.810 --> 00:10:57.110
you know, to the occasion?

00:10:57.110 --> 00:11:00.600
What happens if you've been
beaten down all your life,

00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:03.300
and you don't choose, you
know, the better path?

00:11:03.300 --> 00:11:06.100
You know, what happens to you,
and can you come back from that?

00:11:06.100 --> 00:11:10.050
You know, can you be redeemed
after doing terrible things?

00:11:10.050 --> 00:11:14.130
So that was a lot of what it went
into the making of The Young Elites

00:11:14.130 --> 00:11:16.640
and the making of Adelina,
and Adelina, you know,

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:20.740
I said that I identify with Emika
the most, but every single one

00:11:20.740 --> 00:11:25.100
of my characters has a piece of
myself in Adelina is no different.

00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:26.400
&gt;&gt; Nora Krug: You seem so nice.

00:11:26.400 --> 00:11:27.700
&gt;&gt; Marie Lu: I don't know
what that says about me.

00:11:27.700 --> 00:11:33.750 position:56%
You know, I try to draw on those
times when I've been angry or bitter

00:11:33.750 --> 00:11:37.700
about things, or when people have,
you know, maybe not been good to me

00:11:37.700 --> 00:11:39.580
or when I haven't been
good to people,

00:11:39.580 --> 00:11:42.330
and all of that went
into making Adelina.

00:11:42.330 --> 00:11:44.460
She is like the darker side of me,

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:47.410
and the darker side
of people, I think.

00:11:47.410 --> 00:11:49.920
And, you know, it doesn't
mean that she's all dark.

00:11:49.920 --> 00:11:51.460
You know, she still
loves her sister.

00:11:51.460 --> 00:11:57.080
She has things that she
believes in, and she has a drive,

00:11:57.080 --> 00:11:58.380
and she has vulnerabilities.

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:01.130
She was -- I love, love,
loved creating her,

00:12:01.130 --> 00:12:03.050
even though it was very
hard to be in her headspace.

00:12:03.050 --> 00:12:04.830
&gt;&gt; Nora Krug: I was going to
say, what's it like being there

00:12:04.830 --> 00:12:06.690
and how do you cope with that?

00:12:06.690 --> 00:12:07.990
&gt;&gt; Marie Lu: It's rough.

00:12:07.990 --> 00:12:12.500
I had to listen to a lot of happy
music and dog pile with my dogs

00:12:12.500 --> 00:12:13.820
at the end of every workday,

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:16.650
and sneak in writing
on Warcross as I went.

00:12:16.650 --> 00:12:21.450
So I actually had to --
I had this little habit

00:12:21.450 --> 00:12:23.390
that I would do every morning
